556
00:34:15,018 --> 00:34:17,282
You can make this up to me by,
by, by cleaning up this mess.

557
00:34:17,421 --> 00:34:18,080
You're lucky I don't,

558
00:34:18,155 --> 00:34:20,282
I don't cut the whole staff and
let you do it by yourself.

559
00:34:20,624 --> 00:34:21,591
Manny. Manny.

560
00:34:22,959 --> 00:34:25,018
I, I have to do this now...man.

561
00:34:25,128 --> 00:34:25,594
What?

562
00:34:25,662 --> 00:34:26,287
I have to go.

563
00:34:26,363 --> 00:34:27,330
What?

564
00:34:27,464 --> 00:34:28,590
What's everybody staring at?

565
00:34:28,665 --> 00:34:29,222
We have work...

566
00:34:29,299 --> 00:34:29,993
You!

567
00:34:30,067 --> 00:34:31,796
In my office, right now!

568
00:34:42,913 --> 00:34:43,743
I called everyone.

569
00:34:43,847 --> 00:34:45,246
I called Mama, Papa.

570
00:34:46,249 --> 00:34:47,841
You left all of us
when you walked out of

571
00:34:47,951 --> 00:34:49,213
that door with
your new friend.

572
00:34:49,286 --> 00:34:51,117
Two tabl-- Hm.

573
00:34:53,156 --> 00:34:55,283
Two tables walked out
on us today, Jose.

574
00:34:55,392 --> 00:34:55,983
Two.

575
00:34:56,093 --> 00:34:57,117
That's never happened before.

576
00:34:57,227 --> 00:34:57,852
Never.

577
00:34:57,928 --> 00:34:59,691
This is, this is bad business, Jose.

578
00:34:59,763 --> 00:35:01,162
Bad business.

579
00:35:01,865 --> 00:35:03,594
Everything to you is business.

580
00:35:04,301 --> 00:35:06,929
I'm sure everyone picked up
the slack and got you...

581
00:35:07,037 --> 00:35:08,629
...and your restaurant
through the day.

582
00:35:08,772 --> 00:35:11,138
But what are you doing for them?

583
00:35:12,742 --> 00:35:13,640
Wait, wait, wait, wait.

584
00:35:13,710 --> 00:35:14,938
Am I hearing this correctly?

585
00:35:15,045 --> 00:35:16,774
A-Ask Amelia.

586
00:35:16,847 --> 00:35:17,939
She's been here the whole time.

587
00:35:18,014 --> 00:35:18,912
She has four kids

588
00:35:18,982 --> 00:35:20,643
and commutes from
the Bronx every day.

589
00:35:20,717 --> 00:35:21,809
She has three kids, Manny.

590
00:35:21,885 --> 00:35:22,715
She has kids.

591
00:35:22,786 --> 00:35:23,775
See?

592
00:35:24,087 --> 00:35:25,452
You don't even know her.

593
00:35:25,822 --> 00:35:27,949
And you're giving the Amelia speech to me?

594
00:35:32,562 --> 00:35:35,656
you're just leaving for
some late, drunk waitress?

595
00:35:35,732 --> 00:35:37,063
When did this happen?

596
00:35:38,869 --> 00:35:40,996
You fired a pregnant woman, Manny.

597
00:35:52,449 --> 00:35:54,747
I don't know why she was late,
all I know is she was late,

598
00:35:54,851 --> 00:35:55,749
all the time.

599
00:35:55,919 --> 00:35:57,284
Did you ever stop to ask?

600
00:35:58,321 --> 00:36:02,121
I mean, do you know anything about
any of these people, besides Amelia?

601
00:36:02,359 --> 00:36:04,384
Do you know that Henri the bartender

602
00:36:04,461 --> 00:36:06,520
is making twice as much as
Pepito, my cook?

603
00:36:09,766 --> 00:36:12,428
Why does Kevin always get better
stations than Margarita?

604
00:36:18,008 --> 00:36:19,475
Enter.

605
00:36:27,817 --> 00:36:28,784
What is wrong with you?!

606
00:36:28,885 --> 00:36:31,319
How can you talk to me like that
in front of my employees?!

607
00:36:31,421 --> 00:36:32,217
What is wrong with me?!

608
00:36:32,289 --> 00:36:33,517
What is it with you?

609
00:36:36,259 --> 00:36:40,662
Carlos, Carlos, one of your people
he's below minimum wage, man!

610
00:36:40,764 --> 00:36:42,459
Why is that, huh?

611
00:36:42,766 --> 00:36:46,258
Oh, he doesn't have papers,
so you can get away with it?

612
00:36:53,143 --> 00:36:54,974
It's all about you, man!

613
00:36:57,847 --> 00:36:59,075
Jose?

614
00:37:04,154 --> 00:37:06,816
This is the same pot you bought
four years ago when you opened.

615
00:37:07,324 --> 00:37:09,224
It scorches because it's old.

616
00:37:10,627 --> 00:37:12,117
Buy another one.

617
00:37:16,399 --> 00:37:18,390
You can clean out
your locker, too.

618
00:37:19,069 --> 00:37:20,502
I'm done.

619
00:37:23,406 --> 00:37:26,170
And call Mama.

620
00:37:26,776 --> 00:37:28,209
She's worried.

621
00:37:38,521 --> 00:37:40,011
What're you trying to do?

622
00:37:56,306 --> 00:37:58,069
Are you all right?

623
00:37:59,409 --> 00:38:01,036
What happened?

624
00:38:04,648 --> 00:38:05,478
Let's go.

625
00:38:05,582 --> 00:38:08,142
Don't tell me he fired you?

626
00:38:10,954 --> 00:38:12,353
I can't believe him!

627
00:38:12,455 --> 00:38:13,046
He's such a piece of

628
00:38:13,123 --> 00:38:14,818
He's been good to me.

629
00:38:21,264 --> 00:38:22,322
All right.

630
00:38:22,599 --> 00:38:24,726
Well, I guess we did ruin his day.

631
00:38:28,138 --> 00:38:29,969
I got some things for the trip..

632
00:38:30,940 --> 00:38:31,998
Let's go.

633
00:39:26,129 --> 00:39:29,963
I could really use a bath,
and some Marvin Gaye.

634
00:39:30,133 --> 00:39:31,930
You can take a bath at my parents'.

635
00:39:32,001 --> 00:39:34,595
They may have Tito Puente,
I don't know about Marvin Gaye.

636
00:39:34,671 --> 00:39:36,764
I thought we were
going to the beach.

637
00:39:36,840 --> 00:39:38,364
They live on the beach.

638
00:39:38,475 --> 00:39:39,601
Don't worry.

639
00:39:39,676 --> 00:39:41,371
Oh, I don't worry.

640
00:39:41,845 --> 00:39:45,508
I used to worry,
but then I did a little research

641
00:39:45,915 --> 00:39:50,978
and I found out that
ten out of ten people...

642
00:39:51,755 --> 00:39:54,383
Do you think that
this is all there is?

643
00:39:54,657 --> 00:39:56,784
That we only live once?

644
00:39:56,926 --> 00:40:01,363
Well, so far I haven't met anyone
who's lived twice.

645
00:40:13,910 --> 00:40:16,276
- Can I ask you a question?
- No.

646
00:40:17,147 --> 00:40:18,307
All right.

647
00:40:18,815 --> 00:40:19,907
I'm just kidding.

648
00:40:19,983 --> 00:40:20,784
What?

649
00:40:20,784 --> 00:40:22,149
Nothing.

650
00:40:23,286 --> 00:40:25,186
Just ask.

651
00:40:29,859 --> 00:40:31,724
Have you thought about adoption?

652
00:40:34,364 --> 00:40:36,924
Do we have to talk about
this right now?

653
00:40:37,534 --> 00:40:39,001
No.

654
00:40:50,847 --> 00:40:53,907
I can't carry a
living thing inside my body

655
00:40:53,983 --> 00:40:56,315
for nine months,
and then, what?

656
00:40:56,453 --> 00:40:59,581
Leave it on a doorstep in
a basket for some stranger?

657
00:41:02,459 --> 00:41:04,654
To me, that's worse than anything.

658
00:41:05,295 --> 00:41:07,286
It doesn't have to be a stranger.

659
00:41:08,698 --> 00:41:11,496
So then I just start
calling up relatives?

660
00:41:11,734 --> 00:41:13,292
My relative?

661
00:41:13,703 --> 00:41:16,035
Hey, Mom, I haven't
talked to you in four years

662
00:41:16,139 --> 00:41:18,630
but I got something for you.

663
00:41:21,845 --> 00:41:23,540
Or how about this?

664
00:41:24,214 --> 00:41:25,806
You can have it.

665
00:41:27,183 --> 00:41:29,947
I bet Manny could
teach it a thing or two.

666
00:41:31,354 --> 00:41:33,288
The Suviran boys can
raise little Nina...

667
00:41:33,356 --> 00:41:34,015
...because right now,

668
00:41:34,090 --> 00:41:37,321
you're probably the only person
in the world I trust.

669
00:41:54,010 --> 00:41:56,501
- Thank you.
- You're welcome.

670
00:42:27,110 --> 00:42:28,543
Nina, Nina.

671
00:42:28,678 --> 00:42:29,610
Wait, wait.

672
00:42:29,679 --> 00:42:31,078
Hold the train.

673
00:43:17,205 --> 00:43:18,433
It's beautiful.

674
00:43:32,187 --> 00:43:33,347
What did he say?

675
00:43:33,588 --> 00:43:35,647
He said you look like a Mexican.

676
00:43:35,757 --> 00:43:37,952
Oh, thank you.

677
00:43:47,969 --> 00:43:49,834
He's inviting us for dinner.

678
00:43:50,038 --> 00:43:51,528
Yo entiendo.

679
00:43:52,307 --> 00:43:53,706
Should we stay?

680
00:44:22,270 --> 00:44:24,761
We're going to help him
plant these trees, all right?

681
00:44:47,229 --> 00:44:48,594
What did he say?

682
00:44:48,964 --> 00:44:51,194
He asked if you liked flowers.

683
00:44:51,433 --> 00:44:52,400
Oh!

684
00:44:53,401 --> 00:44:54,299
Yes.

685
00:44:54,402 --> 00:44:55,232
I do.

686
00:44:55,337 --> 00:44:56,861
I love flowers.

687
00:46:23,825 --> 00:46:25,816
Okay, what just happened?

688
00:46:28,129 --> 00:46:29,323
What?

689
00:46:31,199 --> 00:46:32,530
Nothing.

690
00:46:34,402 --> 00:46:35,562
Wow!

691
00:46:38,740 --> 00:46:39,934
Oh, man.

692
00:46:42,544 --> 00:46:43,841
Does it run?

693
00:46:44,946 --> 00:46:46,174
Let's see.

694
00:46:48,116 --> 00:46:50,277
My dad used to have an old Ford.

695
00:46:53,021 --> 00:46:54,249
Wow!

696
00:46:57,826 --> 00:46:59,191
Is it yours?

697
00:47:00,061 --> 00:47:01,153
Yeah.

698
00:47:01,396 --> 00:47:02,385
Well....

699
00:47:05,133 --> 00:47:06,725
I got the scarf.

700
00:47:07,268 --> 00:47:09,429
We should take a road trip
across the country.

701
00:47:11,072 --> 00:47:13,131
Doesn,t look like
you drive it much.

702
00:47:13,742 --> 00:47:15,073
I used to.

703
00:47:16,111 --> 00:47:18,511
When was the last time
you drove this thing?

704
00:47:21,549 --> 00:47:23,608
The last time I drove it
I went to jail.

705
00:47:29,557 --> 00:47:30,888
Car.

706
00:47:31,259 --> 00:47:32,726
You went to jail?

707
00:47:33,028 --> 00:47:34,427
For what?

708
00:47:35,997 --> 00:47:39,933
Five years ago, I was on my way
to a press conference.

709
00:47:41,669 --> 00:47:44,331
I had just signed a contract with
a new soccer team.

710
00:47:45,573 --> 00:47:47,234
You played soccer?

711
00:47:49,144 --> 00:47:51,271
Everything happened so fast.

712
00:47:51,346 --> 00:47:52,938
Two, one....

713
00:47:53,014 --> 00:47:54,982
Ready or not, here I come.

714
00:47:55,050 --> 00:47:56,677
Cheese!

715
00:47:56,951 --> 00:48:01,285
Sweetie this is the part
where you're supposed to hide.

716
00:48:08,463 --> 00:48:11,762
Luchee I can see you.

717
00:48:11,866 --> 00:48:13,561
- I see you.
- I see you.

718
00:48:15,737 --> 00:48:18,900
We're gonna play this game a lot
when we go to your grandmother's.

719
00:48:19,007 --> 00:48:22,602
And she has horses
and pigs and cows.

720
00:48:22,710 --> 00:48:25,008
Moo, that's right.

721
00:48:31,119 --> 00:48:32,984
Okay, Luchee, ready to play again?

722
00:48:33,221 --> 00:48:35,746
- Yes.
- Okay.

723
00:48:37,058 --> 00:48:38,457
I'm gonna count.

724
00:48:42,664 --> 00:48:50,002
Nine...eight...seven....

725
00:48:55,610 --> 00:48:57,305
Mommy!

726
00:48:58,913 --> 00:49:00,904
Four, three...

727
00:49:02,650 --> 00:49:03,776
...one!

728
00:49:25,507 --> 00:49:27,873
Where are you?

729
00:49:35,583 --> 00:49:37,483
Luchee?

730
00:49:37,619 --> 00:49:39,120
Where are you?

731
00:49:39,120 --> 00:49:41,054
I'm coming.

732
00:49:51,399 --> 00:49:52,991
Luce?

733
00:49:56,037 --> 00:49:57,197
Luchee!

734
00:50:10,084 --> 00:50:11,574
Luchee!

735
00:50:20,228 --> 00:50:24,426
Standing in the middle of the street,
looking down at her little body.

736
00:50:28,770 --> 00:50:31,000
Somebody call an ambulance!

737
00:50:31,172 --> 00:50:33,299
Somebody help me!

738
00:50:33,408 --> 00:50:35,433
I live with it every day, Nina

739
00:50:38,112 --> 00:50:39,409
You!!

740
00:50:39,647 --> 00:50:41,342
It was you!

741
00:50:56,030 --> 00:50:57,793
I can still hear her crying

742
00:50:57,899 --> 00:51:00,527
and screaming for God to
give her daughter back.

743
00:51:00,635 --> 00:51:01,226
Why?!

744
00:51:01,436 --> 00:51:04,064
You killed her!

745
00:51:10,478 --> 00:51:14,608
When I saw her mother holding,
holding her dead child....

746
00:51:35,503 --> 00:51:37,994
I was convicted on
involuntary manslaughter.

747
00:51:42,510 --> 00:51:45,035
My brother Manny was there
all the time with me.

748
00:51:47,782 --> 00:51:49,579
What about her family?

749
00:51:50,151 --> 00:51:52,051
She was a single mother.

750
00:51:53,755 --> 00:51:58,954
They took four years of my life,
and I took everything she had.

751
00:51:59,694 --> 00:52:03,130
I tried to meet with her several times,
but she refused.

752
00:52:03,331 --> 00:52:08,268
I know all she sees in me is
the one who killed her little baby.

753
00:52:09,904 --> 00:52:12,896
- But it was an accident.
- It doesn't matter, Nina.

754
00:52:13,107 --> 00:52:14,369
It doesn't matter.

755
00:52:14,475 --> 00:52:17,205
What matters is that
I took her daughter's life.

756
00:52:22,283 --> 00:52:23,341
Hey, bro!

757
00:52:23,651 --> 00:52:25,278
Que paso?

758
00:52:25,486 --> 00:52:27,283
And Nina, all right.

759
00:52:28,790 --> 00:52:30,985
Are you guys ready to
meet the love of my life?

760
00:52:33,861 --> 00:52:35,988
I think this is it, hermano.

761
00:52:36,164 --> 00:52:37,927
I'm going to marry her.

762
00:52:40,501 --> 00:52:42,992
How long have you guys
been together?

763
00:52:43,638 --> 00:52:45,105
A week.

764
00:52:57,418 --> 00:52:59,318
They want you in the kitchen.

765
00:53:00,421 --> 00:53:01,888
All right.

766
00:53:11,432 --> 00:53:13,093
I promised you a bath.

767
00:53:31,853 --> 00:53:33,411
It's good to see you again.

768
00:53:34,422 --> 00:53:35,684
Nina, right?

769
00:53:35,757 --> 00:53:36,917
Right.

770
00:53:37,525 --> 00:53:40,289
So the two of you
took the day off?

771
00:53:43,231 --> 00:53:46,166
I was kind of fired today.

772
00:53:47,101 --> 00:53:48,363
Yeah, I heard.

773
00:53:48,436 --> 00:53:49,664
I spoke to Manny.

774
00:53:50,538 --> 00:53:51,732
I'm sorry.

775
00:53:53,007 --> 00:53:54,872
You shouldn't take it
personally though.

776
00:53:57,211 --> 00:54:00,703
Do you need to borrow any clothes,
because you could try some of mine.

777
00:54:00,815 --> 00:54:02,476
No, thank you.

778
00:54:02,650 --> 00:54:04,379
Everything I need
is right in here.

779
00:54:04,452 --> 00:54:06,613
I just have to freshen up a bit.

780
00:58:51,939 --> 00:58:56,399
Jose, Nina, Veronica
''Suviran,'' mi novia.

781
00:58:56,510 --> 00:58:59,172
- Nice to meet you.
- Veronica Kustella.

782
00:58:59,346 --> 00:59:01,314
- It's nice to meet you.
- You too.

783
00:59:01,816 --> 00:59:02,783
Novia?

784
00:59:02,983 --> 00:59:04,416
Novia means girlfriend.

785
00:59:04,618 --> 00:59:06,813
Futura esposa
means future wife.

786
00:59:07,221 --> 00:59:08,882
Eduardo is loco.

787
00:59:09,023 --> 00:59:10,991
He's trying to teach me Spanish.

788
00:59:11,759 --> 00:59:13,784
- Some tequila?
- No.

789
00:59:14,028 --> 00:59:15,052
No, no, no.

790
00:59:15,129 --> 00:59:16,357
Family custom, yes.

791
00:59:20,134 --> 00:59:21,658
- Jose?
- No, gracias.

792
00:59:21,769 --> 00:59:23,100
Come on, hermano.

793
00:59:24,572 --> 00:59:26,062
Veronica?

794
00:59:26,440 --> 00:59:27,236
Thank you.

795
00:59:31,979 --> 00:59:33,446
Are we going to toast?

796
00:59:35,616 --> 00:59:38,312
- Shall we say grace?
- Want to say grace?

797
00:59:44,792 --> 00:59:47,488
Veronica and I are going to say Grace.

798
00:59:47,862 --> 00:59:49,193
You ready?

799
00:59:49,830 --> 00:59:50,854
Repeat after me.

800
00:59:57,538 --> 00:59:59,768
This is for Veronica.

801
01:00:00,007 --> 01:00:01,201
Thank you.

802
01:00:01,342 --> 01:00:02,309
Sorry.

803
01:00:21,262 --> 01:00:22,490
Great job!

804
01:00:24,365 --> 01:00:25,730
Now we can toast.

805
01:00:42,983 --> 01:00:44,974
Do you like oysters?

806
01:00:46,020 --> 01:00:47,385
That was good, Dad!

807
01:00:51,225 --> 01:00:52,988
I love oysters.

808
01:00:54,428 --> 01:00:57,659
One time I dove into this river,
in my ranch in Mexico...

809
01:01:00,968 --> 01:01:03,368
...and when I dove in my legs
were sticking out of the water...

810
01:01:03,437 --> 01:01:05,735
...and my whole head
was stuck in mud.

811
01:01:06,106 --> 01:01:08,597
I found out the river
was only three feet deep.

812
01:01:08,776 --> 01:01:11,574
Manny had to come to my rescue
and pull me out by my legs...

813
01:01:11,645 --> 01:01:15,046
...and when he pulled me out
an oyster shell cut my arm.

814
01:01:15,516 --> 01:01:17,416
stitches.

815
01:01:17,785 --> 01:01:19,980
If I had moved my arm
inches to the right...

816
01:01:20,688 --> 01:01:22,918
...this scar would
have been right on my face.

817
01:01:23,390 --> 01:01:25,915
And beautiful Veronica
wouldn't be here.

818
01:01:26,527 --> 01:01:27,960
Why wouldn't I be here?

819
01:01:29,129 --> 01:01:30,858
Because I wouldn't be as handsome.

820
01:01:39,373 --> 01:01:43,139
Anyway, so, Manny fired you
because you were late?

821
01:01:46,347 --> 01:01:48,747
And, you, you walked out on him, today?

822
01:01:57,625 --> 01:02:00,116
Manny fired me too,
before I even started working.

823
01:02:00,194 --> 01:02:01,058
You never showed up for work.

824
01:02:01,161 --> 01:02:02,958
Manny needs to learn how to cook, anyway.

825
01:02:03,030 --> 01:02:06,488
He's too busy cracking
the whip like El General.

826
01:02:07,401 --> 01:02:09,665
El General up on his fine horse.

827
01:02:09,803 --> 01:02:12,431
We should get a statue and put
it in front of the restaurant.

828
01:02:12,640 --> 01:02:14,369
You should take Manny as an example.

829
01:02:14,475 --> 01:02:16,136
He's worked hard all his life.

830
01:02:16,243 --> 01:02:18,234
He started from zero
and look where he is now.

831
01:02:18,712 --> 01:02:19,872
Unlike you.

832
01:02:38,699 --> 01:02:40,792
I don't normally share this,

833
01:02:40,901 --> 01:02:45,304
but in the early years,
we couldn't have children.

834
01:02:46,573 --> 01:02:47,870
We tried.

835
01:02:48,042 --> 01:02:49,304
We tried hard.

836
01:02:49,443 --> 01:02:51,070
We did everything we could, but--

837
01:02:51,679 --> 01:02:54,239
Mom, don't mention such things
in front of the children.

838
01:02:59,320 --> 01:03:03,484
And then when we were about to
give up one of his cousins

839
01:03:03,624 --> 01:03:06,184
back in Puerto Rico
was a social worker...

840
01:03:06,327 --> 01:03:10,593
...and before we knew it we
had adopted this beautiful baby.

841
01:03:11,165 --> 01:03:13,690
He was not even three years old.

842
01:03:14,535 --> 01:03:16,503
A really precious boy.

843
01:03:18,639 --> 01:03:21,767
I think the only difference
between my three sons

844
01:03:21,976 --> 01:03:24,968
is the way
that Manny came to us.

845
01:04:18,899 --> 01:04:20,161
Soccer.

846
01:04:26,306 --> 01:04:28,103
I don't play soccer.

847
01:04:28,275 --> 01:04:28,969
You play soccer?

848
01:04:59,706 --> 01:05:01,173
I'm sorry.

849
01:05:56,096 --> 01:05:58,963
He's saying you can't play soccer
without passion.

850
01:06:01,735 --> 01:06:05,466
This man has never wanted to
learn English in his whole life.

851
01:06:05,572 --> 01:06:06,596
Have you?

852
01:06:08,709 --> 01:06:12,645
I understand what he's saying.

853
01:06:14,581 --> 01:06:16,913
He understands a lot
more than you think.

854
01:06:17,017 --> 01:06:18,075
Don't you?

855
01:06:36,803 --> 01:06:38,270
Well, it's getting late.

856
01:06:38,539 --> 01:06:40,632
I need to get back to the city.

857
01:06:42,576 --> 01:06:44,635
You, Jose, eh, stay here.

858
01:06:45,312 --> 01:06:47,041
You see how he speaks English?

859
01:06:47,181 --> 01:06:49,376
He doesn't because he's lazy.

860
01:06:49,483 --> 01:06:50,609
But he's right.

861
01:06:51,151 --> 01:06:52,982
You should stay here and rest.

862
01:06:53,987 --> 01:06:57,889
Thank you, but I, I really can't.

863
01:07:13,273 --> 01:07:14,763
Take care.

864
01:07:42,169 --> 01:07:43,636
I need to go home.

865
01:07:46,173 --> 01:07:47,868
Let's go to the beach first.

866
01:07:47,975 --> 01:07:49,374
And then we'll go from there.

867
01:07:52,512 --> 01:07:53,843
Sure.

868
01:07:58,685 --> 01:07:59,947
This is for you.

869
01:08:37,124 --> 01:08:40,355
I never saw anything like this...before.

870
01:08:40,527 --> 01:08:41,858
My father made them.

871
01:08:42,062 --> 01:08:44,963
I mean, I think he has
too much time on his hands.

872
01:08:46,266 --> 01:08:47,460
I just adore him.

873
01:08:47,534 --> 01:08:51,197
He is so great.

874
01:08:53,106 --> 01:08:54,505
Is he from Mexico?

875
01:08:54,574 --> 01:08:55,404
No.

876
01:08:55,475 --> 01:08:58,308
My father is from Puerto Rico
and my mother is from Mexico.

877
01:08:58,378 --> 01:09:01,347
So I am a Rico-Mex.

878
01:09:01,882 --> 01:09:04,817
It means half Puerto Rican,
half Mexican.

879
01:09:04,885 --> 01:09:07,046
It's all the same to me.

880
01:09:08,021 --> 01:09:10,421
So is it always like that?

881
01:09:10,490 --> 01:09:12,958
I mean, did you grow up with that?

882
01:09:14,227 --> 01:09:15,251
What?

883
01:09:15,395 --> 01:09:18,262
Joy? Love?

884
01:09:19,433 --> 01:09:20,991
Oh, that's nothing.

885
01:09:21,268 --> 01:09:25,534
I mean, when my whole family
gets together, whew, muchacha!

886
01:09:26,173 --> 01:09:28,300
I mean, it's really crazy.

887
01:09:28,408 --> 01:09:32,572
The food, the music, the dancing,
the salsa, merengue.

888
01:09:34,448 --> 01:09:35,745
It's beautiful.

889
01:09:43,256 --> 01:09:46,885
What does Manny feel about people
knowing he's adopted?

890
01:09:47,661 --> 01:09:49,526
To us, it doesn't make a difference.

891
01:09:53,567 --> 01:09:58,402
You are seriously lucky.

892
01:09:59,940 --> 01:10:02,738
You have a good family.

893
01:10:06,947 --> 01:10:08,642
How about your family?

894
01:10:08,782 --> 01:10:11,751
My dad passed away
when I was twelve.

895
01:10:12,252 --> 01:10:14,447
No brothers or sisters.

896
01:10:15,322 --> 01:10:17,256
So that's my family.

897
01:10:27,934 --> 01:10:29,367
Here.

898
01:10:33,440 --> 01:10:34,998
Thank you.

899
01:10:35,108 --> 01:10:36,598
What about your mom?

900
01:10:39,746 --> 01:10:43,807
After he died she just
kind of sat on the couch

901
01:10:43,884 --> 01:10:47,251
with the remote and
never moved on.

902
01:10:47,621 --> 01:10:49,486
I raised myself.

903
01:10:50,157 --> 01:10:51,886
And her.

904
01:10:52,325 --> 01:10:54,919
How was it dealing with
your dad's death?

905
01:10:56,096 --> 01:10:57,688
I don't know.

906
01:11:00,200 --> 01:11:04,466
I don't remember what the
twelve year old in me was feeling.

907
01:11:09,910 --> 01:11:12,811
I think that my mom
took it so hard

908
01:11:12,913 --> 01:11:16,849
that I didn't get the chance to
grieve, in a healthy way.

909
01:11:17,484 --> 01:11:20,715
It was like I had to
take care of her, you know?

910
01:11:21,421 --> 01:11:23,218
At first,
it brought us closer together

911
01:11:23,356 --> 01:11:26,086
but I eventually turned into
the typical teenager

912
01:11:26,193 --> 01:11:29,890
and all that grief
turned into resentment.

913
01:11:32,833 --> 01:11:37,031
One night,
I got stoned out of my mind.

914
01:11:37,604 --> 01:11:39,663
I went home, walked in her room

915
01:11:39,739 --> 01:11:45,644
and there she was watching TV.

916
01:11:46,213 --> 01:11:51,845
I looked at her and
started laughing at her.

917
01:11:53,487 --> 01:11:56,047
Pointing right in her face.

918
01:12:00,961 --> 01:12:04,920
She just sat there.

919
01:12:15,308 --> 01:12:17,674
And I started to cry.

920
01:12:24,117 --> 01:12:30,750
I told her how much
I miss my dad, too.

921
01:12:32,859 --> 01:12:37,489
That I know that she's in pain
where I was in pain, too.

922
01:12:42,369 --> 01:12:46,567
And it was like for the
first time she saw me again.

923
01:12:54,447 --> 01:12:59,578
She stood up and held me.

924
01:13:10,864 --> 01:13:12,798
Then I got the munchies.

925
01:13:15,402 --> 01:13:19,168
And we ate some doughnuts and
talked about him all night.

926
01:13:23,443 --> 01:13:28,380
The next morning, I woke up
and felt like I had a mom again,

927
01:13:28,715 --> 01:13:35,052
but it was too late.

928
01:14:06,119 --> 01:14:09,179
When I was eighteen,
my mom held out her hand.

929
01:14:10,256 --> 01:14:14,022
She waved her wedding ring
at me this tiny stone

930
01:14:14,094 --> 01:14:16,688
my dad probably
got at a pawn shop.

931
01:14:17,998 --> 01:14:20,899
She said, ''You need to
get you one of these.''

932
01:14:22,736 --> 01:14:26,069
She loved him so much
she never took that ring off.

933
01:14:28,041 --> 01:14:30,339
That's what I want, Jose.

934
01:14:31,344 --> 01:14:35,110
I want to bring a child
into this world out of love...

935
01:14:35,448 --> 01:14:38,144
...with a man who's
gonna take care of us.

936
01:14:40,987 --> 01:14:42,921
I don't have that.

937
01:14:45,191 --> 01:14:50,060
I can't have this baby
and watch it suffer with me.

938
01:14:56,169 --> 01:14:58,797
I don't know what I'm doing.

939
01:15:05,178 --> 01:15:08,204
I'm gonna need a friend next week.

940
01:16:33,600 --> 01:16:34,658
Here.

941
01:16:35,301 --> 01:16:37,201
I want you to keep it.

942
01:16:40,940 --> 01:16:42,066
Thank you.

943
01:16:43,443 --> 01:16:45,104
You're gonna come with me, right?

944
01:16:48,748 --> 01:16:51,216
You know what,
don't worry about it.

945
01:16:51,451 --> 01:16:52,918
I'll be fine.

946
01:16:54,087 --> 01:16:55,554
I'll call you.

947
01:16:58,424 --> 01:16:59,857
I'll call you, okay?

948
01:19:28,141 --> 01:19:32,441
Let's talk about the salmon,
the special I want to come up with.

949
01:19:32,979 --> 01:19:35,971
Asparagus, mushroom, cactus.

950
01:19:36,115 --> 01:19:40,074
I'm gonna throw in some avocado,
some mango.

951
01:19:40,186 --> 01:19:41,448
Manny.

952
01:19:44,223 --> 01:19:45,986
You're gonna do what?

953
01:21:08,341 --> 01:21:09,740
Okay, let's go.

954
01:21:17,050 --> 01:21:19,484
You can always take a piece of
the ocean with you.

955
01:21:19,685 --> 01:21:20,583
How?

956
01:21:20,686 --> 01:21:25,851
When you take a seashell home,
you put it right to your ears

957
01:21:26,059 --> 01:21:27,856
and you can hear the ocean.

958
01:21:29,028 --> 01:21:30,359
You want to try it?

959
01:21:31,064 --> 01:21:32,053
Sure.

960
01:21:32,165 --> 01:21:33,359
Okay.

961
01:21:33,766 --> 01:21:35,791
One, two, three.

962
01:21:37,804 --> 01:21:39,931
Here. Try.

963
01:21:44,210 --> 01:21:45,609
I can't hear it yet.

964
01:21:45,711 --> 01:21:48,578
Oh, well,
you're at the ocean.

965
01:21:48,981 --> 01:21:51,882
But when you leave the ocean,
then you can hear it.

966
01:21:57,323 --> 01:21:59,917
- I can hear it now.
- You can hear now?

967
01:22:08,000 --> 01:22:09,467
Perfect.

968
01:22:17,143 --> 01:22:20,635
- How do I look?
- You look beautiful.

969
01:22:32,625 --> 01:22:34,320
Here she comes.

970
01:22:40,933 --> 01:22:42,423
Okay. Let's go.

971
01:23:35,555 --> 01:23:38,285
Do you know who I am?

972
01:23:39,458 --> 01:23:41,255
You're my mama.

973
01:23:52,004 --> 01:23:54,438
I brought this for you.

974
01:24:00,546 --> 01:24:04,209
That was the last gift
my father gave to me.

975
01:24:12,158 --> 01:24:13,785
Thank you.

976
01:24:15,494 --> 01:24:17,086
You're welcome.

977
01:24:29,442 --> 01:24:31,171
Thank you.

978
01:24:31,310 --> 01:24:33,005
You're welcome.

979
01:24:40,753 --> 01:24:44,621
Jose thank you so much.

980
01:24:46,492 --> 01:24:48,050
I'm sorry.

981
01:24:48,160 --> 01:24:50,458
Thank you. Thank you.

